Linked List

A linked list a linear DS that includes a series of connected Data structures.

Each node consists of a data value and a pointer that points to the next node.

Order of node is not given by physical placement of their memory, instead each node points top the next.
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Advantage of linked List using over array 

The list elements can be easily inserted or removed without reallocation or reorganization of the entire structure.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Disadvantage 

Random access of element is not feasible and accessing an element has linear time complexity -O(n)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

The linked List Data structure supports 3 main operations

1) Insertion: to add an element at the beginning, end or at a given index in the list
2) Deletion: to remove an item given its index or value
3) Search: To find an element given its value.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


Series of connected nodes
data| pointer to next node --------------> data| pointer to next node -------------->data | Null

pointer of last data is null. It does not point any where else.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Usage of Linked List

All applications of both stack and queues are applications of linked list.

